</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C322DFC52816FF878CB7B217FA5FFA52" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2816FF878CB7B217FA5FFA52" blockId="13.[151,1437,1250,2033]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis id="B94C505C2816FF878CB7B217FE9DFAB7" bold="true" box="[199,322,1358,1384]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C38F7CD2816FF878D3BB216FE7BFAB6" authorityName="Savigny" authorityYear="1818" box="[331,420,1359,1385]" class="Polychaeta" family="Amphinomidae" genus="Chloeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphinomida" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94C505C2816FF878D3BB216FE7BFAB6" box="[331,420,1359,1385]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Chloeia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with ventral cirri of similar size throughout body; bipinnate branchiae from chaetiger 4; dorsum with a round, blackish spot surrounded by pale areas per segment; chaetal bundles homogeneously pale.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C322DFC52816FF878CB7B2CFFD60F875" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2816FF878CB7B2CFFC0EF9C2" blockId="13.[151,1437,1250,2033]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis id="B94C505C2816FF878CB7B2CFFE86FA6F" bold="true" box="[199,345,1430,1456]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Description.</emphasis>
Best preserved specimen (USNM 46277) complete, 
<quantity id="4CC021AB2816FF878FECB2CFFC35FA6E" box="[924,1002,1430,1457]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="85.0">85 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="4CC021AB2816FF87885CB2CFFBA6FA6E" box="[1068,1145,1430,1457]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
wide, 38 chaetigers. Body fusiform; dorsal pigmentation pattern consists of a central dark brown circle or round spot per segment positioned towards posterior border of each segment, and brown pigmentation around the lateral side under branchiae and notochaetal lobes of prededent segments (
<figureCitation id="130390CB2816FF878E1DB15AFD38F9C2" box="[621,743,1539,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-116@12.[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chloeia flava (Pallas, 1766). A. Illustration of complete specimen from Pallas (1766). B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Pigmentation pattern from median segments (Photo: Elizabeth Borda). D. Neurochaeta from median chaetigers. E–G. Notochaetae, black arrows indicate position of spurs (Li: lips, LL: lateral (plicated basal) lobes, MA: median antenna, ML: median (plicate) lobe, Pa: palps, PA: paired antennae). Scale bars: B, 2 mm; C, 1 mm; D–F, 20 μm; G, 10 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480001/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Fig. 6A, C</figureCitation>
). Chaetae yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2816FF878CB7B17EFE88F90E" blockId="13.[151,1437,1250,2033]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">
Prostomium semicircular with four black eyes, anterior eyes 2–3× larger than posterior ones (
<figureCitation id="130390CB2816FF8788ABB17EFAECF99D" box="[1243,1331,1575,1602]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-116@12.[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chloeia flava (Pallas, 1766). A. Illustration of complete specimen from Pallas (1766). B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Pigmentation pattern from median segments (Photo: Elizabeth Borda). D. Neurochaeta from median chaetigers. E–G. Notochaetae, black arrows indicate position of spurs (Li: lips, LL: lateral (plicated basal) lobes, MA: median antenna, ML: median (plicate) lobe, Pa: palps, PA: paired antennae). Scale bars: B, 2 mm; C, 1 mm; D–F, 20 μm; G, 10 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480001/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
). Median antenna arising from anterior caruncle region, longer than lateral antennae and palps. Caruncle with a V-shaped posterior margin (
<quantity id="4CC021AB2816FF878D12B137FE64F956" box="[354,443,1646,1673]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
long); median lobe with about 30 folds. Lateral basal lobes spread, each with a similar number of folds, without pigmentation. Mouth ventral on chaetiger 3. Bipinnate branchiae from chaetiger 4, present throughout body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2816FF878CB7B182FC71F8E2" blockId="13.[151,1437,1250,2033]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Parapodia biramous. Notopodia with cirriform branchiae along chaetigers 1–4, progressively decreasing in size, subsequent chaetigers with branchiae bipinnate. Cirriform branchiae present in chaetiger 4 smaller than preceding ones. Neuropodia with second ventral cirri as long as contiguous ones.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2816FF878CB7B01EFD60F875" blockId="13.[151,1437,1250,2033]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">
Neurochaetae furcates; relative length of tines 1:3–1:4 (
<figureCitation id="130390CB2816FF878F36B01EFC7DF8BD" box="[838,930,1863,1890]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-116@12.[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chloeia flava (Pallas, 1766). A. Illustration of complete specimen from Pallas (1766). B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Pigmentation pattern from median segments (Photo: Elizabeth Borda). D. Neurochaeta from median chaetigers. E–G. Notochaetae, black arrows indicate position of spurs (Li: lips, LL: lateral (plicated basal) lobes, MA: median antenna, ML: median (plicate) lobe, Pa: palps, PA: paired antennae). Scale bars: B, 2 mm; C, 1 mm; D–F, 20 μm; G, 10 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480001/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Fig. 6D</figureCitation>
). Notochaetae with serrated external border, short tine very short, like a spur (
<figureCitation id="130390CB2816FF878D8AB032FDACF859" box="[506,627,1899,1926]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-116@12.[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chloeia flava (Pallas, 1766). A. Illustration of complete specimen from Pallas (1766). B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Pigmentation pattern from median segments (Photo: Elizabeth Borda). D. Neurochaeta from median chaetigers. E–G. Notochaetae, black arrows indicate position of spurs (Li: lips, LL: lateral (plicated basal) lobes, MA: median antenna, ML: median (plicate) lobe, Pa: palps, PA: paired antennae). Scale bars: B, 2 mm; C, 1 mm; D–F, 20 μm; G, 10 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480001/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Fig. 6E–G</figureCitation>
). Serrated external border consists of few teeth (3–8) or border completely serrated with more than 20 denticles (
<figureCitation id="130390CB2816FF878E4DB0D6FD6CF875" box="[573,691,1935,1962]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-116@12.[151,1436,381,1881]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 6. Chloeia flava (Pallas, 1766). A. Illustration of complete specimen from Pallas (1766). B. Anterior end, dorsal view. C. Pigmentation pattern from median segments (Photo: Elizabeth Borda). D. Neurochaeta from median chaetigers. E–G. Notochaetae, black arrows indicate position of spurs (Li: lips, LL: lateral (plicated basal) lobes, MA: median antenna, ML: median (plicate) lobe, Pa: palps, PA: paired antennae). Scale bars: B, 2 mm; C, 1 mm; D–F, 20 μm; G, 10 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480001/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Fig. 6E–F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C322DFC52816FF848CB7B0EAFD1BFE55" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="517" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2816FF848CB7B0EAFD1BFE55" blockId="13.[151,1437,1250,2033]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1437,150,429]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="517" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis id="B94C505C2816FF878CB7B0EAFEE4F812" bold="true" box="[199,315,1971,1997]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516">Remarks.</emphasis>
The original description by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2816FF878EF1B0EAFCC8F811" author="Pallas, P. S." box="[641,791,1971,1998]" pageId="13" pageNumber="516" refId="ref24974" refString="Pallas, P. S. (1766) Miscellanea Zoologica. Petrum van Cleef, Hagae Comitum, 224 pp., 14 pls." type="book" year="1766">Pallas (1766)</bibRefCitation>
is adequate with good illustrations, but does not include chaetal features, probably due to lack of microscopes without spheric aberrations. However, chaetal features were illustrated later by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2815FF848D04B7CEFDEAFF6E" author="M'Intosh, W. C." box="[372,565,150,177]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 554" refId="ref24351" refString="M'Intosh, W. C. (1885) Report on the Annelida Polychaeta collected by H. M. S. Challenger during the years 1873 - 76. Challenger Reports, 12, 1 - 554." type="journal article" year="1885">M’Intosh (1885)</bibRefCitation>
. Thus, the delimitation of this species is rather settled, and several authors provided complete characterizations (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2815FF848E38B7E2FD11FF0A" author="Horst, R." box="[584,718,187,213]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 43" refId="ref23777" refString="Horst, R. (1912) Polychaeta Errantia of the Siboga Expedition, Part 1. Amphinomidae. Siboga-Expeditie Leyden, 24 a, 1 - 43." type="book chapter" year="1912">Horst 1912</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2815FF848EAEB7E2FCAFFF0A" author="Fauvel, P." box="[734,880,186,213]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" refId="ref23035" refString="Fauvel, P. (1953) The Fauna of India including Pakistan, Ceylon, Burma and Malaya. Annelida Polychaeta. Indian Press, Allahabad, 507 pp." type="book" year="1953">Fauvel 1953</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2815FF848FF0B7E2FC29FF09" author="Day, J. H." box="[896,1014,187,214]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 878" refId="ref22273" refString="Day, J. H. (1967) A Monograph on the Polychaeta of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History) Publications, 656, 1 - 878. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 8596" type="journal article" year="1967">Day 1967</bibRefCitation>
). However, the record by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2815FF84895CB7E2FF3DFF26" author="Treadwell, A. L." pageId="14" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref25681" refString="Treadwell, A. L. (1923) Polychaetous annelids from lower California with descriptions of new species. American Museum Novitates, 74, 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="1923">Treadwell (1923)</bibRefCitation>
from San Francisquito Bay, 
<collectingRegion id="49FC42AC2815FF848E47B786FD35FF26" box="[567,746,223,249]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="14" pageNumber="517">Baja California</collectingRegion>
, in the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="49FC42AC2815FF848FD8B786FBC3FF26" box="[936,1052,223,249]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="14" pageNumber="517">California</collectingRegion>
, is questionable because he only provided species name, without any comment about its appearance. Consequently, some illustrations of this species are herein provided to facilitate its identification and to avoid future misidentifications in Eastern Pacific waters. We think Treadwell might have found 
<taxonomicName id="4C38F7CD2815FF848E32B612FC63FEBA" authority="Augener, 1922" authorityName="Augener" authorityYear="1922" box="[578,956,331,357]" class="Polychaeta" family="Amphinomidae" genus="Chloeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphinomida" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="pseudeuglochis">
<emphasis id="B94C505C2815FF848E32B612FD8AFEBA" box="[578,597,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="517">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B94C505C2815FF848E12B612FCD0FEBA" box="[610,783,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="517">pseudeuglochis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA9F1BF2815FF848F65B612FC63FEBA" author="Augener, H." box="[789,956,331,357]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" pagination="38 - 53" refId="ref21238" refString="Augener, H. (1922) Ueber litorale Polychaeten von Westindien. Sitzungsberichte der Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde zu Berlin, 1922 (3 - 5), 38 - 53." type="journal article" year="1922">Augener, 1922</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which was described some time before his contribution was sent for publication (see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C322DFC52815FF848CB7B6CBFC9CFE72" box="[199,835,402,429]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B878C4E2815FF848CB7B6CBFC9CFE72" blockId="14.[151,1437,150,429]" box="[199,835,402,429]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis id="B94C505C2815FF848CB7B6CBFEBEFE73" bold="true" box="[199,353,402,428]" pageId="14" pageNumber="517">Distribution.</emphasis>
Indian Ocean, in shallow water sediments.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
